vectorData.altText: That's right!  The external carotid artery (B) is located posterior to the ramus of the mandible.

The inferior alveolar artery passes through the mandible supplying branches to the mandibular teeth. It ends by emerging from the mental foramen as the mental artery (F) to supply the tissues of the chin.
“stupefy”, because compression of these arteries was thought to cause stupor
posterior to the infratemporal fossa, and trace it to where it ends by dividing into the maxillary artery (B)

and superficial temporal artery (C). The superficial temporal artery crosses the zygomatic process of the temporal bone just anterior to the external auditory meatus. 
Palpate the pulse of the superficial temporal artery on yourself and a lab partner (but take your glove off first). 
On the prosection, if possible (no dissecting!) trace the maxillary artery anteriorly into the infratemporal fossa, as it makes its way toward the pterygomaxillary fissure (D). Part of its course in this particular prosection may be obscured by the pterygoid muscles but it will be seen in its entirety in the specimen of the deep infratemporal fossa. 
In the present specimen, however, identify the inferior alveolar branch of the maxillary artery (E) entering the mandibular canal in the ramus of the mandible. In an intact specimen, the actual point of entry into the mandibular canal is the mandibular foramen.
